@(A.274 = 274-296) Since the time when @wGN{Sumer} and @wGN{Akkad} had been dispersed, no king had introduced a statue into the shining @wTN{E-kur} of @wDN{Enlil} or into the @wTN{E-ŋa-ŋiš-šua} beside @wDN{Ninlil}. @wDN{Enlil} opened the @wTN{E-namtila} to me from his loving heart. In the @wTN{E-kur} I arranged the great treasures, and allocated durable treasuries. For @wDN{Enlil} my master, I erected a throne whose form was beyond form itself. I stood the throne of @wDN{Ninlil} in the @wTN{E-ŋa-ŋiš-šua} in the @wTN{Ki-ur}, the great place. The throne of @wDN{Enlil} is not to be removed from there. I, @wRN{Išme-@wDN{Dagan}}, son of @wDN{Dagan}, stood the throne for @wDN{Enlil} my master on a dais …… of seven storms, decorated in a masterly and highly skilled manner with @fsux{nir-igi} and @fsux{šuba} stones and translucent lapis lazuli, and I seated @wDN{Enlil} there with my lady @wDN{Ninlil}. I put them into a favourable mood, with happy hearts; I delighted @wDN{Enlil} greatly with those thrones. I measured (?) my gift (?) for him, and my heartfelt act (?) delighted @wDN{Enlil}.

